  "title": "Tereu",
  "sourceFile": "Waste_notes/tereu_N.htm",
  "encoding": "windows-1252",
  "html": "\n<div><center>\n<table>\n<tr>\n<td><font><img src=\"../images/R.gif\"/> </font><b>Tereu\n        ... </b><hr noshade=\"\"/>\n<p>Latin vocative from of Tereus, who \"rudely\n        forc'd\" Philomela; it was also one of the\n        conventional words for a nightingale's song in\n        Elizabethan poetry. Cf. the song from John Lyly's <i>Alexander\n        and Campaspe</i> (1564): </p>\n<p>Oh, 'tis the ravished nightingale.<br/>\n<i>Jug, jug, jug, jug, tereu!</i> she cries,\"</p>\n<p>and lines 100ff. (NA)</p>\n<p><font><em>reference topics</em></font></p>\n<table>\n<tr>\n<td>John Lyly's <i>Alexander and Campaspe</i></td>\n<td><a href=\"title_A.htm\"><img src=\"../images/arrowry.gif\"/></a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"Tereus_OM.htm\">Ovid's\n                <i>Metamorphoses</i>, <br/>\n                The Story of Tereus, Procne and Philomela</a></td>\n<td><a href=\"title_A.htm\"><img src=\"../images/arrowry.gif\"/></a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"Waste_A.htm\"><font>back to \"The Waste Land\" </font></a></td>\n<td><a href=\"Burbank_A.htm\"><img src=\"../images/arrowry.gif\"/></a></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</center></div>\n",
  "text": "Tereu ... Latin vocative from of Tereus, who \"rudely forc'd\" Philomela; it was also one of the conventional words for a nightingale's song in Elizabethan poetry. Cf. the song from John Lyly's Alexander and Campaspe (1564): Oh, 'tis the ravished nightingale. Jug, jug, jug, jug, tereu! she cries,\" and lines 100ff. (NA) reference topics John Lyly's Alexander and Campaspe Ovid's Metamorphoses , The Story of Tereus, Procne and Philomela back to \"The Waste Land\"",
